Aspect-oriented programming.

There is a whole class of behaviour that does not really belong to any single component, but instead cuts across many of them: logging, transactions, security checks, metrics, retries. We call these cross-cutting concerns. Aspect-oriented programming, or A-O-P, lets you write such behaviour exactly once and then apply it to many methods, instead of copy-pasting it into every one.

There are four vocabulary words to learn. An aspect is a class that holds cross-cutting behaviour. An advice is a method on that aspect that runs at some point, and the three kinds are at-before, at-after, and at-around. A pointcut is an expression that selects which target methods the advice should apply to. And a join point is one specific intercepted method execution. So a timing aspect might use an at-around advice, with a pointcut matching any public method under your service package, to record how long every service call takes. The at-around advice receives a proceeding join point, and it calls proceed to run the real method in the middle, wrapping timing around it.

Here is how Spring makes this work, and it connects straight back to module seven. Spring wraps every bean whose methods match a pointcut in a proxy. That proxy intercepts the calls and runs your advice around them. This is not a niche feature; it is a core mechanism. The very same proxying is what powers at-transactional, at-cacheable, and Spring Security's method security. There is one important gotcha, though. Because the proxy sits between callers and the bean, A-O-P only intercepts calls that come into the bean from outside. If a bean calls one of its own methods, through this-dot-other, that call goes directly, bypasses the proxy, and skips the advice entirely.
